        <p>Taxes are one of the places single dads quietly lose money — not because they did anything wrong, but because nobody told them what they qualified for. Filing status and credits can mean thousands of dollars a year. This is a plain-language overview of the big ones. It's not tax advice — rules change and situations differ — but it'll tell you what to look into and ask about.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The single most valuable question:</strong> are you filing as <strong>Head of Household</strong> rather than Single? If you have a qualifying child living with you more than half the year and you pay more than half the cost of keeping up your home, you likely can — and it means a bigger standard deduction and better tax brackets than filing Single. Many eligible single dads file Single by mistake and overpay.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Head of Household status</h2>
        <p>This is usually the biggest single lever for a single dad. To qualify, in general you need to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Be unmarried (or "considered unmarried") on the last day of the year;</li>
          <li>Have a qualifying child or dependent who lived with you more than half the year; and</li>
          <li>Have paid more than half the cost of keeping up your home for the year.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The payoff is a larger standard deduction and more favorable brackets than Single status. If you share custody, pay close attention to the "more than half the year" residency test — it's about where the child actually lived, counted in nights.</p>

        <h2>Who claims the kids in shared custody</h2>
        <p>This is where co-parents most often collide. The basic rules:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Only one parent can claim a given child as a dependent in a given year.</strong> You can't both claim the same child.</li>
          <li><strong>By default, the "custodial parent"</strong> — the one the child lived with for more nights during the year — has the right to claim the child.</li>
          <li><strong>The custodial parent can release the claim</strong> to the other parent using IRS <strong>Form 8332</strong>. Many divorce decrees specify who claims the child, or alternate it year to year — but the IRS generally requires Form 8332 to actually transfer the dependency claim.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep your own records</strong> of overnights. If both parents claim the same child, the IRS applies "tiebreaker" rules and someone's return gets adjusted — usually the one without the residency claim.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If your custody arrangement addresses who claims the kids, make sure your actual filing matches it. Disputes here are common and avoidable with clear records. See <a href="{{ '/legal/custody/' | url }}">Custody &amp; Visitation</a> for how these terms live in a parenting plan.</p>

        <h2>Credits worth knowing about</h2>

        <h3>Child Tax Credit</h3>
        <p>A per-child credit for qualifying children under the age limit, subject to income phase-outs. It's claimed by whoever claims the child as a dependent — another reason the dependency question above matters. The exact amount and thresholds change, so check the current year's figures on <a href="https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/child-tax-credit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IRS.gov</a>.</p>

        <h3>Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC)</h3>
        <p>A credit for low-to-moderate-income workers that's significantly larger if you have qualifying children. It's <em>refundable</em> — meaning it can put money in your pocket even if you owe no tax. A lot of eligible single dads never claim it. If your income is modest, check whether you qualify; it can be one of the largest credits available.</p>

        <h3>Child and Dependent Care Credit</h3>
        <p>If you pay for childcare so you can work or look for work — daycare, after-school care, a summer day camp — you may be able to claim a credit for part of those costs. Keep receipts and the provider's tax ID. This pairs directly with the <a href="{{ '/resources/childcare-school/' | url }}">Childcare &amp; School</a> logistics.</p>

        <h2>Practical tips</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Free filing is available</strong> if your income is below the IRS Free File threshold — see <a href="https://www.irs.gov/filing/free-file-do-your-federal-taxes-for-free" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IRS Free File</a>. Don't pay to file if you don't have to.</li>
          <li><strong>Free in-person help exists too:</strong> the IRS <a href="https://www.irs.gov/individuals/free-tax-return-preparation-for-qualifying-taxpayers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VITA program</a> offers free tax prep for people who qualify, often at libraries and community centers.</li>
          <li><strong>Adjust your withholding</strong> if you switched to Head of Household or your dependents changed — update your W-4 with your employer so you're not over- or under-withheld all year.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep a simple custody-overnight log.</strong> It's the documentation that settles dependency questions if they ever come up.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>When to get a professional.</strong> If your custody or income situation is complicated — mid-year changes, self-employment, a dispute over who claims the kids — a one-time session with a tax professional often pays for itself many times over. For straightforward situations, free filing tools handle it fine.</p>
        </div>

        <p>For the month-to-month money side, see <a href="{{ '/financial/budgeting/' | url }}">Budgeting on One Income</a>; if things are tight right now, <a href="{{ '/financial/assistance/' | url }}">Assistance Programs</a> covers help you may qualify for.</p>

        <p><em>This page is general information, not tax advice. Tax rules change yearly and depend on your specific situation — confirm details at <a href="https://www.irs.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IRS.gov</a> or with a qualified tax professional.</em></p>
